title: WORKSHOP | Yes, you can host a house party!
description:
**Why host a house party?**  Yes, door knocks, phone banks, postcards, rallies are all important organizing tools.  But in 2025-26, we need to do something more and different to win.  House parties can:

- Reach voters outside of our political bubbles

- Have friend and neighbor conversations with those who support our democratic values

- Inoculate voters against the onslaught of right-wing media

- Expand our volunteer base

**Are you thinking about hosting a house party, but don't know how to get started?**  If you've never hosted one before (and even if you're a fellow introvert), or just want a refresher, join the Bay Area Coalition every Monday, 7 pm (PT) for our ** *California-wide* ** house party workshop ...

 - How to plan your house party

 - Tips and tools for hosting conversations with your friends, neighbors, colleagues

 - Learn PDI-on-the-GO to find your local Democrats, or others who share our values

*You'll leave the workshop fired up and ready to host your house party!*

Sign up here for ** *nationwide* ** house party workshops every Monday, 5 pm (PT) / 7 pm (CT) / 8 pm (ET) - https://www.mobilize.us/cadems/event/778676/

For more Bay Area Coalition actions: https://bayareacoalition.org/

title: Stop Elon Musk Rally!
description:
### Join Indivisible Greater Vancouver (IGV) and MoveOn-Clark County for a peaceful protest at Vancouver's Tesla dealership! 

Unvetted DOGE operatives hired by Musk are accessing our data, impounding funds allocated by Congress, and crippling federal agencies. This empowers the surveillance state and paves the way for billionaire tax cuts, deregulation and more. 

We'll march on the sidewalk/right of way outside Vancouver's Tesla showroom on Fourth Plain Blvd., staying on public property. Park on the street or in the surrounding neighborhood. Bring a large sign to let everyone know we stand united against Musk, DOGE, and unelected oligarchs!

### NEW SATURDAY TIMES 
Through the month of May our Saturday Stop Elon Musk! rallies will be from 4 pm - 6 pm. We've made this time change to allow people to attend more than one event on Saturdays. Thank you for your dedication to showing up for democracy!

We at IGV strongly believe that peaceful, non-violent activism offers social movements the most power to effect change. Through peaceful protests, we set an example of making our voices heard with dignity, empowered by truth. IGV does not condone intimidation, threats, vandalism, interference with access to a business, or any other lawless actions. If instigators or our opponents attempt to violate our commitment to non-violence, we will try to de-escalate them and will end the event if needed to maintain a safe environment.

title: Invasive Vine Removal at Woodlawn Cemetery

sponsor.name: Chesapeake Climate Action Network / Action Fund

description:
Join Meredith from CCAN to remove Invasive Vines at the historic Woodlawn Cemetery in Washington, DC. 

We will meet at the entrance to the cemetery off of Benning Rd. SE at 9am. Parking is available inside the gates - do not park on the street.

We will spend the first 30 minutes doing a brief training on invasive vines and best practices for removal, and spend about 2 hours removing vines from the trees. We will focus on non-native invasive vines including porcelainberry (Ampelopsis glandulosa var. brevipedunculata) and English ivy (Hedera helix).

Please wear long pants, long sleeves, and close-toed shoes. Instructions and tools will be provided, so just bring yourself and a good attitude!

A reminder email will be sent out the day before with detailed instructions on where to meet.

title: TRAIL DAY: Hueston Woods State Park
description:
Come out to help build and maintain the trails at Hueston Woods! We will be doing a variety of tasks throughout the spring and summer to keep everything in great shape, including working on the trail tread itself, clearing drainages around the trail to help manage water, and clearing vegetation to mitigate invasives and maintain safe lines of sight for trail users. 

Please contact isaac@coratrails.org with any questions.

title: ARIZONA! Holding Space: A Listening & Wellness Phone Bank
description:
Join Supermajority Arizona on the last Monday of the month, at 6 PM for Holding Space, a phone bank rooted in connection, care, and community. The work doesn’t stop after the election—this is about checking in with women in our state, hearing what’s on their minds, and keeping our movement strong.

We’ll be making calls to first-time women voters from the 2024 election cycle, creating space to listen, share, and keep the conversation going about the issues that matter. Now more than ever, staying connected and engaged is how we build power for 2025 and beyond. Let’s show up for each other and for the future we deserve.

title: NO KINGS Peaceful Rally
description:
Donald Trump's attempts to claim the powers of an absolute monarch must be stopped.  

The Constitution grants Congress the power of the purse, but Trump is ignoring Congress' budgets, levying new taxes, and converting taxpayer dollars into useless crypto.

description:
Election Day poll greeting involves volunteers stationed outside polling places to welcome voters, provide sample ballots, and offer any needed assistance or information. This friendly presence ensures that voters feel supported and informed as they exercise their right to vote.

**In local elections, where outcomes can hinge on a small number of votes, the role of poll greeters is crucial in maximizing voter turnout and ensuring a smooth voting experience.**

**Never poll greeted before?** Don't worry, we'll provide training!

### Why is Poll Greeting Important?
1. **Voter Assistance:** Poll greeters can answer last-minute questions, direct voters to the correct polling locations, and provide information on voting procedures, reducing confusion and wait times.
2. **Encouragement:** A warm welcome can boost voter morale and reinforce the importance of their participation in the democratic process.
3. **Education:** Poll greeters help ensure voters are informed about their choices before entering the polling place by distributing sample ballots and information about candidates or issues.

### Frequently Asked Questions

**What exactly is Poll Greeting?**
Poll Greeters are the friendly faces you see outside your polling place who distribute sample ballots and answer questions.

**What do I need to bring?**
We recommend wearing comfortable shoes and weather appropriate clothing, and bringing a charged phone to help look up information for voters if they have questions. Optionally, you can bring a chair, table, or pop-up tent; a speaker to play appropriate music (be weary you don't play music too loudly); and snacks to hand out to voters.

**What is provided to Poll Greeters?**
We'll provide all of the materials and signs you need. Additionally, we provide each shift food and water.

title: Deep Canvass Institute 101: Foundational Skills of Deep Canvassing
description:
**Please note that this is a three-session training. You must be signed up for and complete all three sessions - Tuesday, Wednesday, and Saturday in order to receive your certificate of completion. Click "Select All (3 times)" at signup** 

Just curious about deep canvassing but not sure you’re ready to commit to a nine-hour training? Register for our virtual info session, “An Introduction to Deep Canvassing” to learn more at https://deepcanvass.fyi/rsvp-intro

The Deep Canvass Institute is offering this 101 training where you will be trained in the fundamental skills of deep canvassing. 

Deep canvassing was developed by organizers and volunteers in the LGBTQ+ rights movement as a way to turn the tide of a decade of losses around marriage equality. At its heart, deep canvassing and its underlying skills, are tools we use to create a more fair and caring country by talking directly with people we don’t know and who might disagree with us. When we listen to someone, share stories about our own lives, and approach the conversation with compassionate curiosity and a non-judgmental approach, it makes both of us more willing to take actions toward making our country more caring and equitable.

Deep Canvass Institute 101 Foundational Skills Training:

- SESSION 1 of 3: **Tuesday, May 13 at 6:00 p.m ET** we’ll dive into the deep canvass conversation structure and how to tell your personal story with vulnerability.

- SESSION 2 of 3: **Wednesday, May 14 at 6:00 p.m. ET** we explore the critical skills of compassionate curiosity & active listening, and we provide an overview of the script we’ll be using on Day 3.

- SESSION 3 of 3: **Saturday, May 17 at 12:00 p.m. ET** you’ll have a chance to role play the script, have your first conversation with a stranger using the fundamental skills you've learned, and debrief with experienced deep canvassers, all in the Deep Canvass Institute’s training environment.

**The Deep Canvass Institute is a training program created in collaboration between New Conversation Institute and People's Action Institute. This training is non-partisan. We will not discuss or take questions on deep canvassing in the context of candidate elections or parties.**

title: Introduction to Deep Canvassing: The Proven Method to Change Hearts and Minds
description:
**This is an information session, not a training. This session will help you understand if you want to attend our three-session 101: Foundational Skills of Deep Canvassing training.**

Are you an organizer, community leader, or activist looking to engage with your community around deeply polarizing issues? Are you an individual hoping to understand how to have compassionate, non-judgmental conversations across lines of difference? Or, are you someone who’s heard about this thing called “deep canvassing” and you’re curious to learn more?

Join The Deep Canvass Institute on Tuesday, March 25 from 6:00 - 7:00 p.m. ET for a virtual information session to learn more about deep canvassing; what it is, how it’s used and why it works. This is an info session, not a training.

This information session will cover the core components of deep canvassing and help you decide if our three-session “Deep Canvass Institute 101: How to Have a Deep Canvass Conversation” is for you.

You'll have the opportunity to register for this no-cost training after the information session.

Deep canvassing was developed by organizers and volunteers in the LGBTQ rights movement as a way to turn the tide of a decade of losses around marriage equality. It has since become the one of the only tactics scientifically proven to be able to lastingly reduce prejudice, inoculate people against fear-based messaging, and change hearts and minds on our most divisive issues like immigration, climate change, transgender justice, abortion, voting rights, and more.

When we take this approach, people’s experience leads them away from prejudice, stigma, or fear, and towards empathy and a willingness to consider equitable solutions.

Deep canvassing is featured in the book “How to Change Minds: The New Science of Belief, Opinion and Persuasion” by David McRaney, writer for the Atlantic and Psychology Today. It is also featured in the book “The Persuaders: At The Front Line Of The Fight For Hearts, Minds And Democracy” by New York Times best-selling author, Anand Giridharadas.

**The Deep Canvass Institute is a training program created in collaboration between New Conversation Institute and People's Action Institute. This training is non-partisan. We will not discuss or take questions on deep canvassing in the context of candidate elections or parties.**

title: Open House with the United Vision Project

sponsor.name: The United Vision Project & National Training Hub

description:
At United Vision Project, we are devoted to the long-term project of bridging and healing the deep divides that have brought us to this moment of systemic collapse. We do this by reaching out and listening deeply to people with whom we deeply disagree. We develop the capacity to bring humility, empathy, curiosity, and respect to contentious conversations with strangers, so that we can bring these same qualities to hard conversations with our friends, family, coworkers, and neighbors. 

Since 2021, United Vision Project has reached out to over 1.4 million people across twelve states via text message, leading to thousands of meaningful conversations across extreme political difference. Who are the people sending these texts, and who are they texting? Is it really possible to have a meaningful conversation with someone whose politics and perspective are extremely different? What becomes possible when we start to understand the genuine grievances underneath all the noise in our political climate and conversations? 

If you’re curious and want to learn more, we invite you to join us for an interactive, one-hour open house where we’ll introduce you to United Vision Project’s signature training and program on Authentic Relational Conversations. During our time together we will:

- Answer the above questions, and more!
- Share more information about the Authentic Relational Conversations training and program, and help you get signed up if you’re interested 
- Play simple games or engage in small group activities to learn and practice some of the skills that make Authentic Relational Conversations possible

description:
**Please note that this is a three-session training. You must be signed up for and complete all three sessions - Tuesday, Wednesday, and Saturday in order to receive your certificate of completion. Click "Select All (3 times)" at signup** 

Just curious about deep canvassing but not sure you’re ready to commit to a nine-hour training? Register for our virtual info session, “An Introduction to Deep Canvassing” to learn more at https://deepcanvass.fyi/rsvp-intro

The Deep Canvass Institute is offering this 101 training where you will be trained in the fundamental skills of deep canvassing. 

Deep canvassing was developed by organizers and volunteers in the LGBTQ+ rights movement as a way to turn the tide of a decade of losses around marriage equality. At its heart, deep canvassing and its underlying skills, are tools we use to create a more fair and caring country by talking directly with people we don’t know and who might disagree with us. When we listen to someone, share stories about our own lives, and approach the conversation with compassionate curiosity and a non-judgmental approach, it makes both of us more willing to take actions toward making our country more caring and equitable.

Deep Canvass Institute 101 Foundational Skills Training:

5. May 30-  ANOTHER NAME FOR NONVIOLENCE? DEMOCRACY! Beyond political parties, factions, and radical wings, right and left, democracy is an ecosystem that is relational and takes a lot of work. Authoritarianism is, frankly, easier, providing you trust power holders to serve your interests. But that kind of power is corrupting, and although democracy takes a lot of work, it is our only sustainable way forward.

title: Office Hours Film: Learn about Stonewall
description:
## Let's kick off Pride Month by looking back at what activists accomplished during and after the Stonewall uprising. ##

In the early morning hours of June 28, 1969, police raided the Stonewall Inn, a popular gay bar in the Greenwich Village section of New York City. Such raids were not unusual in the late 1960s. That night, however, the street erupted into violent protests and demonstrations that lasted for the next six days. The Stonewall riots, as they came to be known, marked a major turning point in the modern gay civil rights movement in the United States and around the world.

Discussion to follow!
